      <!-- Section 1 -->
      <section id="what-is-context-optimisation" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>What LLM Context Optimisation Means</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>LLM context optimisation is the practice of engineering content structure so that the right information is preserved — and correctly attributed — after the retrieval and extraction process that AI systems apply before generating a response.</strong>
          It is a layer of technical content work that sits beneath the visible quality of writing and determines whether good content is actually usable by an AI system.
        </p>

        <p>
          Most content strategy discussions focus on what is written: the quality of arguments, the depth of evidence, the accuracy of claims. Context optimisation focuses on how content is written: the size of paragraphs, the structure of headings, the self-sufficiency of individual passages, and the token efficiency of each section. These structural properties determine what survives when an AI system breaks a document into pieces, retrieves the most relevant pieces, and assembles them into a context window.
        </p>

        <p>
          LLM context optimisation is closely related to — but distinct from — <a href="/llm-visibility-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">LLM visibility optimisation</a>. Visibility optimisation addresses whether your brand appears in AI responses; context optimisation addresses whether the content that does appear is extracted accurately and completely. Both are required for a functional <a href="/ai-brand-visibility/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">AI brand visibility</a> programme, and both feed into the broader <a href="/generative-engine-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">generative engine optimisation</a> discipline.
        </p>

        <h3>Why This Is a Separate Discipline</h3>
        <p>
          A page with excellent prose quality but poor context structure can produce misleading AI citations: the model retrieves a chunk that contains part of a nuanced argument, extracts it without the qualifications in adjacent chunks, and presents a simplified or distorted version as a citation. The brand is cited — but inaccurately. Context optimisation is the structural discipline that prevents this failure mode, ensuring that every extractable unit of content delivers an accurate, attributable representation of the brand's expertise.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 2 -->
      <section id="chunking-mechanics" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>How Content Chunking Works in AI Retrieval</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>Chunking is the process by which a retrieval system divides a document into discrete segments before indexing — and it is the single most consequential processing step for determining whether content is cited accurately.</strong>
          Understanding how it works allows content writers to structure documents that perform well regardless of which chunking strategy a given platform uses.
        </p>

        <p>
          Retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) systems cannot insert an entire document into a context window — documents are too long and context windows are finite. Instead, the system chunks documents into segments, embeds each chunk as a vector, and stores those vectors in an index. At query time, the system embeds the query, retrieves the most semantically similar chunks, and inserts them into the context window alongside the query.
        </p>

        <h3>Fixed-Size Chunking</h3>
        <p>
          Fixed-size chunking splits documents at regular token intervals — for example, every 256 or 512 tokens — with or without an overlap window. It is the simplest and most commonly used approach. Its failure mode is boundary splitting: a chunk that begins mid-argument or mid-sentence provides incomplete context to the model. Content writers can mitigate this by ensuring every paragraph is a complete, self-contained unit that makes sense at any position within a fixed-size window.
        </p>

        <h3>Sentence and Paragraph Chunking</h3>
        <p>
          Sentence and paragraph chunking splits at natural language boundaries — full stops or paragraph breaks. This approach preserves grammatical completeness but can still lose structural context when a paragraph references concepts established many paragraphs earlier. The mitigation is the same: write paragraphs that are contextually self-sufficient, not reliant on cross-paragraph reference chains.
        </p>

        <h3>Semantic Chunking</h3>
        <p>
          Semantic chunking uses embeddings to identify topic transitions within a document and splits at those boundaries. It is the most context-preserving approach but is computationally expensive and not universally deployed. Content structured with clear topical sections — each introduced by an explicit heading and developed within 150–400 words before transitioning — performs optimally under semantic chunking because the section boundaries align naturally with the semantic splits.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 3 -->
      <section id="context-window" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>Context Windows: What They Are and Why They Constrain Content</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>A context window is the total amount of text a language model can read and reason over in a single inference — and the chunks retrieved from your content must fit within it alongside the query and the model's system prompt.</strong>
          Even models with large context windows (100,000+ tokens) typically insert only a small number of retrieved chunks per query, because relevance scoring limits how many sources are injected.
        </p>

        <p>
          In practice, a RAG pipeline typically inserts between two and eight retrieved chunks into the context window. If each chunk is 300 tokens, that represents 600–2,400 tokens of retrieved content. This means that for any given query, only a small fraction of your total content is ever read by the model — specifically, the chunks that scored highest on semantic similarity to the query.
        </p>

        <p>
          The implication for content structure is significant: every section of your content must be capable of independently supporting a citation, because you cannot predict or control which sections will be retrieved for a given query. A page with a strong introduction but a weak middle section will be cited well when the introduction's chunk is retrieved and cited poorly or not at all when a middle-section chunk is retrieved.
        </p>

        <h3>Token Budget Efficiency</h3>
        <p>
          Token budget efficiency is the ratio of meaningful, citable content to total tokens in a chunk. Long preambles, transitional phrases, and hedging language consume token budget without contributing citable content. Content optimised for token efficiency places the key claim in the first sentence of each paragraph, uses precise language rather than hedged commentary, and avoids throat-clearing introductions that delay the informational payload. This is not a stylistic choice — it is a structural property that directly affects which claims appear in the retrievable portion of each chunk.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 4 -->
      <section id="writing-self-contained" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>Writing Self-Contained Passages</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>The self-contained passage — a unit of text that delivers complete, accurate meaning without requiring surrounding context — is the fundamental building block of context-optimised content.</strong>
          Every paragraph on a citation-targeted page should meet this criterion: if extracted in isolation by a retrieval system, it should convey a correct and attributable representation of the point being made.
        </p>

        <p>
          Writing self-contained passages requires five structural disciplines applied consistently:
        </p>

        <div class="not-prose mt-6 space-y-4">

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">1. Topic sentence first</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              Begin every paragraph with a sentence that states the key claim or definition. Do not build to the point — state it, then support it. "Schema markup reduces AI retrieval ambiguity" is a topic sentence. "When thinking about how structured data interacts with language model retrieval, one consideration worth noting is..." is not.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">2. Eliminate pronoun dependencies</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              Pronouns that refer to entities named in earlier paragraphs break self-containedness. Replace "it", "they", "this approach", and "the above" with full noun references. A chunk that begins "This is most effective when combined with..." is uninterpretable in isolation; a chunk that begins "Entity schema optimisation is most effective when combined with FAQPage markup..." is not.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">3. Include contextual metadata within passages</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              Dates, units, platform names, version numbers, and source names should appear within each passage that cites them, not assumed from a surrounding section header. A reader (or model) who encounters only this paragraph should not need to look elsewhere to understand what platform, timeframe, or organisation is being discussed.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">4. Use headings as standalone labels</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              Section headings serve a dual purpose: they organise the document for human readers and they provide context for the chunks that follow. Headings that function as standalone labels — "Schema Markup for AI Retrieval" rather than "Going Further" — improve the accuracy of semantic chunking and provide context that some retrieval systems prepend to the chunks beneath each heading.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">5. Limit passages to 150–400 words</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              Passages shorter than 150 words often lack sufficient context for accurate extraction. Passages longer than 400 words increase the risk of spanning chunk boundaries and losing tail content. The 150–400 word range optimises for self-containedness, token efficiency, and boundary alignment across the most common chunking strategies deployed in production RAG systems.
            </p>
          </div>

        </div>
      </section>

