      <section id="common-failures" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>Common Context Optimisation Failures</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>Most context optimisation failures are invisible to human readers but detectable in AI citation outputs — the brand is cited, but inaccurately, incompletely, or out of context.</strong>
          Understanding the most common failure modes allows content teams to audit existing pages systematically and prioritise fixes.
        </p>

        <h3>The Inverted Pyramid Problem</h3>
        <p>
          Many content writers follow a journalistic inverted pyramid structure at the page level — leading with the most important information — but then write individual sections in a build-up style that buries the key claim at the end of each paragraph. When a retrieval system extracts the first 200 tokens of such a section, it captures the preamble but not the conclusion. The fix is to apply inverted pyramid structure at the paragraph level, not just the page level: state the claim first, then elaborate.
        </p>

        <h3>The Shared Context Problem</h3>
        <p>
          Content that relies on context established earlier in the same document creates shared-context dependencies that break under chunking. A section titled "Applying This Approach" that refers to a method described three sections earlier becomes meaningless if extracted in isolation. Every section should be written as though the reader has not read the preceding sections — because, in a chunked retrieval context, the model often hasn't.
        </p>

        <h3>The Hedge Chain Problem</h3>
        <p>
          Heavily hedged content — "it might be worth considering whether, in some contexts, there could be an argument that…" — is tokeniser-inefficient and citation-resistant. AI systems prefer confident, attributable claims. Hedging is appropriate where genuine uncertainty exists, but reflexive hedging applied to well-established practices consumes token budget and reduces the extractability of the underlying claim. Replace hedge chains with specific caveats: "This approach is most effective for B2B SaaS brands; consumer product brands may see lower citation uplift."
        </p>

        <p>
          Context optimisation is one layer of the full <a href="/ai-brand-visibility/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">AI brand visibility</a> framework. For platform-specific retrieval patterns across ChatGPT, Perplexity, and Gemini, see our guide to <a href="/optimise-for-ai-platforms/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">optimising for specific AI platforms</a>. For the complete strategic context, see the <a href="/generative-engine-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">generative engine optimisation</a> guide.
        </p>
      </section>

